When THz energy is transmitted into biological materials, the optical energy is absorbed by target chromophores. Once absorbed, this energy is then converted into heat, and in the process generates significant thermal transients, which are the driving force and precursor for all photothermal processes. Thus, in the absence of photochemical processes and phase transitions, all energy absorbed by THz-exposed tissue is converted into a temperature rise. Using the incident THz irradiance and the absorption coefficient for skin, the rate and amount of energy that is deposited into the tissue can be calculated. This rate is typically defined as the rate of heat generation S (Wmâ3):
